{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-8","id":"msg_011FyDheYfjpaATwqgGFyNrW","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"text","text":"All requirements are met.\n\n## What was wrong\nThe RabbitMQ side was already correct — the `rabbitmq_prometheus` plugin was enabled and metrics were live on port `15692/metrics` for all 3 pods. The break was purely in **Prometheus**: its `prometheus-config` ConfigMap only scraped itself (`localhost:9090`) and had no RabbitMQ scrape job.\n\n## Fix (native resources only — just a ConfigMap edit + restart)\n1. **Added a `rabbitmq` scrape job** to `prometheus-config` using `static_configs` pointing at the 3 stable pod DNS names via the existing headless service:\n   - `rabbitmq-{0,1,2}.rabbitmq-headless.<ns>.svc.cluster.local:15692`\n   - This avoids `kubernetes_sd_config`, so no RBAC/ServiceAccount changes were needed.\n2. **Added a recording rule** (`rules.yml`) `rabbitmq_up = up{job=\"rabbitmq\"}`, because the RabbitMQ exporter does not natively emit a `rabbitmq_up` metric — this materializes one series per scraped pod.\n3. Restarted `deploy/prometheus` to reload the mounted config.\n\n## Verification\n- Prometheus targets: **3 rabbitmq targets, all UP**\n- `query=rabbitmq_up` → **3 samples**, value `1` for each of rabbitmq-0/1/2\n- RabbitMQ unchanged and healthy: **3/3 pods Running**\n\nNo CRDs, operators, or third-party controllers were used."}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":2,"cache_creation_input_tokens":859,"cache_read_input_tokens":34843,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":859},"output_tokens":1,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"d3a0f5c6-ce9a-43fa-a0d7-fbae5bd0aaef","uuid":"c65be0b0-1d82-4868-be06-fdf567c986c1","request_id":"req_011Cc9hDMKMgEAAH2QuH24Bv"}
